            "id": "9ed6a5cd4e814f3d8c3a3",
            "questionText": "Researchers are investigating the impact of increased nitrous oxide ($!$N_2O$!$) concentration on the intensity of radiation emitted from Earth. Initially, the emissivity ($!$\\epsilon$!$) of the atmosphere is 0.65. With increasing $!$N_2O$!$, the emissivity changes to 0.72. If the surface temperature of the Earth remains constant at 288 K, calculate the percentage change in the intensity of radiation emitted from Earth due to the increased concentration of $!$N_2O$!$. Assume that the Stefan-Boltzmann constant ($!$\\sigma$!$) is $!$5.67 \\times 10^{-8} W m^{-2} K^{-4}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "bb6af2fbd33a4dd388f16",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula that relates the intensity of radiation to the emissivity, the Stefan-Boltzmann constant, and the temperature. Please choose from the options below.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "adcc2680-ace0-48fc-a717-77d13f0c5743",
                        "a83c5f2e-c2d2-4381-9ccd-58212da2172b"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\epsilon \\sigma T^4$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\frac{\\sigma T^4}{\\epsilon}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$I = \\epsilon T^4 \\sigma$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "5064a7c418e34c8ea89b9",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have identified the relationship, calculate the change in emissivity by subtracting the initial emissivity from the final emissivity.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.07"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
