        {
            "id": "aac16a904c6d4112b891f",
            "questionText": "A climatologist observes that the Earth's albedo has decreased from 0.32 to 0.30 over a decade due to melting ice caps. Given that the solar constant (S) is approximately $!$1400 W/m^2$!$, and assuming that the Earth's emitted radiation (given by $!$\\sigma T^4$!$) balances the absorbed solar radiation, where the Stefan-Boltzmann constant (\\( \\sigma \\)) is $!$5.67\\times10^{-8} W m^{-2} K^{-4}$!$, calculate the corresponding change in Earth's equilibrium temperature (\\( \\Delta T \\)) resulting from this albedo decrease.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "cb346cfd17e3487e8144b",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the energy balance equation at equilibrium that relates Earth's absorbed solar radiation to its emitted radiation. Which of the following represents the correct energy balance equation?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b51ed1b6-771b-45fa-9760-5d85e7688f2a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$(1-\\alpha)\\frac{S}{4} = \\sigma T^4$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$(1-\\alpha)S = \\sigma T^4$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\frac{S}{4} = \\sigma T^4$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "c716f376fc054f3e9d582",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, deduce the expression for Earth's equilibrium temperature in terms of the albedo. Which of the following expressions correctly rearranges the energy balance equation to solve for $!$T$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b51ed1b6-771b-45fa-9760-5d85e7688f2a",
                        "4423e9c4-c105-4183-9ce7-c7d4352e4ec0"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\left[ \\frac{(1-\\alpha)S}{4\\sigma} \\right]^{1/4}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\frac{(1-\\alpha)S}{4\\sigma}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$T = \\left[ \\frac{\\sigma}{(1-\\alpha)S/4} \\right]^{1/4}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "c46f0bfa8c8e4d62a08b3",
                    "stepText": "Using the correct expression, calculate the Earth\u2019s initial equilibrium temperature for an albedo of 0.32. Use $!$S = 1400\\,W/m^2$!$ and $!$\\sigma = 5.67\\times10^{-8}\\,W\\,m^{-2}\\,K^{-4}$!$. What numerical value in Kelvin do you obtain (approximately)?",
